This is a short introduction to pandas!¶

Customarily, we import as follows:

In [7]:
# In python, when using functions from packages, you will need to address where the function is coming from. You can see, when importing a package we give it an alias ('pd', 'np'). You can do this for any imported package you want.

import numpy as np # Numpy works hand-in-hand with pandas often. It's a very large package with a ton of functionality. No need to try and learn all of it at once. You'll pick up on things as you need them
import pandas as pd

Introduction to Data Structures¶

Pandas uses two primary components. These are Series and DataFrames. A series is essentially a column, and a DataFrame is a multi-dimensional table made of a collection of Series. DataFrames and Series are quite similar in that many operations that you can do with one you can do with the other, such as filling in null values and calculating the mean.

Series¶

Series is a one-dimensional labeled array capable of holding any data type (integers, strings, floating point numbers, Python objects, etc.). The axis labels are collectively referred to as the index. The basic method to create a Series is to call:

In [8]:
data = [1, 2, 3, 4] # test list
index = [0, 1, 2 ,3 ] # most pandas objects will naturaly have indicies starting at 0, incrementing by 1 per row
In [9]:
s = pd.Series(data, index=index)
s
Out[9]:
0    1
1    2
2    3
3    4
dtype: int64

DataFrames¶

Creating DataFrames right in Python is good to know and quite useful when testing new methods and functions you find in the pandas docs.

There are many ways to create a DataFrame from scratch, but a great option is to just use a simple dict.

Let's say we have a fruit stand that sells apples and oranges. We want to have a column for each fruit and a row for each customer purchase. To organize this as a dictionary for pandas we could do something like:

In [10]:
data = {  # dict key = column, dict value = list of values, aka our rows for the df
    'apples': [3, 2, 0, 1], 
    'oranges': [0, 3, 7, 2]
}
In [11]:
purchases = pd.DataFrame(data)

purchases
Out[11]:
apples oranges
0 3 0
1 2 3
2 0 7
3 1 2

You may be asking, how did pandas know how to do that? Well, each (key, value) item in data corresponds to a column in the resulting DataFrame.

The Index of this DataFrame was given to us on creation as the numbers 0-3, but we could also create our own when we initialize the DataFrame.

In [12]:
# We could set a custom index like so...
purchases = pd.DataFrame(data, index=['June', 'Robert', 'Lily', 'David'])

purchases
Out[12]:
apples oranges
June 3 0
Robert 2 3
Lily 0 7
David 1 2

In order to select a specific row, we will need to select the correct index. Since we have customer names as the index, it will look something like this...

In [13]:
purchases.loc['June']
Out[13]:
apples     3
oranges    0
Name: June, dtype: int64

Joins¶

The last thing I will cover is somewhat basic on the surface level, but you'll find with data that this can become challenging. Let's discuss joining datasets together. There are mainly three different types of joins you will come across. These are: inner, outer, left/right.

In [36]:
product=pd.DataFrame({
    'Product_ID':[101,102,103,104,105,106,107],
    'Product_name':['Watch','Bag','Shoes','Smartphone','Books','Oil','Laptop'],
    'Category':['Fashion','Fashion','Fashion','Electronics','Study','Grocery','Electronics'],
    'Price':[299.0,1350.50,2999.0,14999.0,145.0,110.0,79999.0],
    'Seller_City':['Delhi','Mumbai','Chennai','Kolkata','Delhi','Chennai','Bengalore']
})
In [38]:
customer=pd.DataFrame({
    'id':[1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9],
    'name':['Olivia','Aditya','Cory','Isabell','Dominic','Tyler','Samuel','Daniel','Jeremy'],
    'age':[20,25,15,10,30,65,35,18,23],
    'Product_ID':[101,0,106,0,103,104,0,0,107],
    'Purchased_Product':['Watch','NA','Oil','NA','Shoes','Smartphone','NA','NA','Laptop'],
    'City':['Mumbai','Delhi','Bangalore','Chennai','Chennai','Delhi','Kolkata','Delhi','Mumbai']
})
In [40]:
# Here we are taking the two dfs above, identifying a like column (ID) and joining 'inner' aka like data (same ID between the two)

pd.merge(product, customer, on='Product_ID', how='inner')
Out[40]:

# If the column names were different but we still wanted to join them on a like column, we'd have to explicitly call the columns
pd.merge(product,customer,left_on='Product_name',right_on='Purchased_Product')

# Maybe we just want to join both of the tables together. We can do this with a outer join. Note, when the rows don't match between the two, the resulting dataframe will have NaN for every column lacking a match.
pd.merge(product,customer,on='Product_ID',how='outer')

# For a left join, all the non-matching rows of the left dataframe contain NaN for the columns in the right dataframe. It is simply an inner join plus all the non-matching rows of the left dataframe 
# filled with NaN for columns of the right dataframe.
pd.merge(product,customer,on='Product_ID',how='left')

# And a right join is just the opposite
# pd.merge(product,customer,on='Product_ID',how='right')

Joins can be complicated to deal with, but familarizing yourself with the data first is a great way to make sure you're not losing data, duplicating data, etc.

This concludes the introduction to pandas. Pandas is crucial to data science with python, and learning the basics will set you up to do majority of the work. Packages like pandas and numpy are super dense, and you will find functions as you need them. https://stackoverflow.com/ will soon become your best friend when working with python. If you can get good at googling, you'll become a great data scientist ;)
